event: response.output_text.delta
data: {"type":"response.output_text.delta","content_index":0,"delta":".","item_id":"msg_0af930b6d9e9e7540169e44e0d85808196b84c77cd84313660","logprobs":[],"obfuscation":"tGNmEQd5FY2RGJE","output_index":1,"sequence_number":670}

event: response.output_text.done
data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0af930b6d9e9e7540169e44e0d85808196b84c77cd84313660","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":671,"text":"Let the three doors be: one has a prize, two have nothing. You pick one door initially. Then the host, who knows where the prize is, opens one of the two doors you didn’t pick, always revealing a goat (i.e., never opens the prize door). You’re then offered the choice to stay with your original door or switch to the remaining unopened door.\n\n### Key logical idea\nYour *initial* choice has a probability of **1/3** of being correct, and **2/3** of being wrong. Those probabilities are determined before any doors are opened, so they don’t “reset” when the host reveals a goat.\n\n### Step-by-step logic (event cases)\nConsider the initial situation:\n\n1) **You initially pick the prize**  \n- Probability: **1/3**  \n- Then the host opens one of the two goat doors (there are two goats to choose from).  \n- If you **switch**, you will lose (you move from prize to goat).  \n- If you **stay**, you win.\n\n2) **You initially pick a goat**  \n- Probability: **2/3**  \n- Then the prize is behind the other unopened door (among the two you didn’t pick).  \n- The host must open the remaining goat door (the only goat available to open).  \n- After the host opens a goat, the **only unopened other door must be the prize**.  \n- If you **switch**, you win.  \n- If you **stay**, you lose.\n\n### Convert cases into final probabilities\n- Switching wins in case (2): probability **2/3**.\n- Staying wins in case (1): probability **1/3**.\n\nSo:\n- **Switching gives 2/3 chance of winning**\n- **Staying gives 1/3 chance of winning**\n\n### Why “it becomes 1/2 and 1/2” is the common mistake\nAfter the host opens one goat door, there are two unopened doors left. But they are **not symmetric** in a probabilistic way.\n\n- Your original door was chosen with probability **1/3** of containing the prize.\n- The combined probability that the prize was in one of the *other two* doors was **2/3**.\n- The host’s action doesn’t change where the prize is; it only removes one goat in a way that depends on the host knowing the prize location.\n\nSo the **entire 2/3 probability** collapses onto the single remaining unopened door when you switch—hence switching wins with probability **2/3**, not **1/2**.\n\nThat’s the core logical reasoning behind the Monte Hall problem."}

