ning the prize.\n- The combined probability that the prize was in one of the *other two* doors was **2/3**.\n- The host’s action doesn’t change where the prize is; it only removes one goat in a way that depends on the host knowing the prize location.\n\nSo the **entire 2/3 probability** collapses onto the single remaining unopened door when you switch—hence switching wins with probability **2/3**, not **1/2**.\n\nThat’s the core logical reasoning behind the Monte Hall problem."},"sequence_number":672}

